- **Latest Version**: Ensure you are using the latest version of React Query to benefit from the most recent features and bug fixes.
- **CLI Commands**:
  - `npx create-react-app my-app --template typescript`
  - `npm install react-query@latest`
- **Key Config Options**:
  - `queryClient`: Configure options for the query client, such as `defaultOptions`.
  - `useQuery`: Use this hook to fetch data. Key options include `queryKey`, `queryFn`, and `options` like `staleTime` and `refetchInterval`.
- **Example Usage**:
  ```typescript
  import { useQuery } from 'react-query';
  import axios from 'axios';

  const fetchUser = async (userId: string) => {
    const response = await axios.get(`https://api.example.com/users/${userId}`);
    return response.data;
  };

  const UserComponent = ({ userId }: { userId: string }) => {
    const { data, isLoading, error } = useQuery(['user', userId], fetchUser);

    if (isLoading) return <div>Loading...</div>;
    if (error) return <div>Error: {error.message}</div>;

    return (
      <div>
        <h1>{data.name}</h1>
        <p>{data.email}</p>
      </div>
    );
  };
  ```

- Install React Query using npm or yarn:
  ```
  npm install react-query@latest
  # or
  yarn add react-query@latest
  ```

- Use `useQuery` for fetching data:
  ```typescript
  import { useQuery } from 'react-query';

  const fetchPosts = async () => {
    const response = await fetch('https://api.example.com/posts');
    return response.json();
  };

  function Posts() {
    const { isLoading, error, data } = useQuery('posts', fetchPosts);

    if (isLoading) return <div>Loading...</div>;
    if (error) return <div>Error: {error.message}</div>;

    return (
      <ul>
        {data.map((post) => (
          <li key={post.id}>{post.title}</li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    );
  }
  ```

- Key config options for `useQuery`:
  - `queryKey`: Unique identifier for the query.
  - `queryFn`: Function that fetches data.
  - `initialData`: Initial data to display while fetching.
  - `staleTime`: Time in milliseconds after which data is considered stale.
  - `refetchInterval`: Interval in milliseconds at which data should be refetched.

- Use `useMutation` for updating data:
  ```typescript
  import { useMutation } from 'react-query';

  const createPost = async (post) => {
    const response = await fetch('https://api.example.com/posts', {
      method: 'POST',
      headers: {
        'Content-Type': 'application/json',
      },
      body: JSON.stringify(post),
    });
    return response.json();
  };

  function CreatePost() {
    const mutation = useMutation(createPost);

    const onSubmit = (event) => {
      event.preventDefault();
      const title = event.target.title.value;
      mutation.mutate({ title });
    };

    return (
      <form onSubmit={onSubmit}>
        <input type="text" name="title" />
        <button type="submit">Create Post</button>
      </form>
    );
  }
  ```

- Key config options for `useMutation`:
  - `mutationFn`: Function that performs the mutation.
  - `onSuccess`: Callback function to handle successful mutations.
  - `onError`: Callback function to handle errors during mutations.

- Use `useQueryClient` to manually trigger refetches or invalidate queries:
  ```typescript
  import { useQueryClient } from 'react-query';

  function InvalidatePosts() {
    const queryClient = useQueryClient();

    const handleClick = () => {
      queryClient.invalidateQueries('posts');
    };

    return (
      <button onClick={handleClick}>Invalidate Posts</button>
    );
  }
  ```

- Key config options for `useQueryClient`:
  - `invalidateQueries`: Invalidate queries based on their keys.
  - `refetchQueries`: Refetch queries based on their keys.

- Use `useIsFetching` to conditionally render UI based on fetching status:
  ```typescript
  import { useQuery, useIsFetching } from 'react-query';

  function Posts() {
    const { isLoading, error, data } = useQuery('posts', fetchPosts);
    const isFetching = useIsFetching();

    if (isLoading) return <div>Loading...</div>;
    if (error) return <div>Error: {error.message}</div>;

    return (
      <ul>
        {data.map((post) => (
          <li key={post.id}>{post.title}</li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    );
  }
  ```

- Key config options for `useIsFetching`:
  - No specific options, returns a boolean indicating if any queries are currently fetching.
